message: /* Imprisonment and release */Mentioned Howard many times, both his position as Duke of Norfolk (mentioning him as Duke or Norfolk) and his last name itself must be alternated in the text.

/* Imprisonment and release */As all the sources cite that the execution of the 3rd Duke was going to be on January 28 and Henry VIII died the same day, so the King died during the early hours of the morning, which is still night time.
/* Rise to power and later career */
Citing that Gardiner was also Bishop of Winchester.
/* Rise to power and later career */
Mentioned twice in the same text the surname of the mother of Howard's first wife.

/* Rise to power and later career */Richmond was a Prince and he became so when he was recognized by his father and given the double title of the Dukedom of Richmond and Somerset. See article about him.
/* Early life */Richard III was Duke of Gloucester, not York.
/* Legal troubles and execution */Replacing Burghley with Cecil.
/* Death and burial */Howard was buried to the right of his first wife. If you look at the effigies from the front in the tomb, Ana is on the left and Thomas is on the right.
/* Spanish marriage */Philip's son, that is, Mary's stepson, was also known as Don Carlos.

/* Spanish marriage */It should also be noted that this possible son could also have been the heir to the throne of Portugal, due to the closeness of Philip II's blood with the Portuguese royal family.

/* Spanish marriage */Mary and Philip were descendants of the Duke of Lancaster through their common ancestor, Catherine of Lancaster, wife of Henry III of Castile, but Mary was also a descendant, through her paternal family, of John Beaufort, 1st Duke of Somerset, legitimized son of Gaunt.
/* Early life, family, and religion */Jane Howard marked because there are sources that cite that she was born in 1533 and there are others that cite that she was born in 1537.
/* Spanish marriage */Adding a little more information: Philip had been widowed a few years ago.

message: I have replaced your phrase ('Tudor dynasty') with 'House of Tudor', which is the correct way of referring to royal houses / families in Britain and other European countries. However, the word 'dynasty' may be used in this context if preceded by the indefinite article, but not if preceded by the definite article. 'Dynasty' is mainly used in connection with Chinese imperial rulers (and the relevant pottery).
